name: The Plastic People of the Universe
Půlnoc
comments: Meaning "Midnight", the band formed out of the break up of Plastic People in the late eighties. Following Czechoslovakia's Velvet Revolution in 1989, Lou Reed discovered the band whilst visiting Prague in 1990. When the The Velvet Underground reunited, Půlnoc were the opening act in Paris for the Andy Warhol exhibition by the Cartier Foundation. The band came together for two short lived reunions in 1996 and 2012.

name: Harry B. Smith
comments: Writer, lyricist and composer and the most prolific of all American stage writers: he is said to have written over 300 librettos and more than 6000 lyrics. Some of his best-known works were librettos for the composers Victor Herbert and Reginald De Koven. He also wrote the book or lyrics for several versions of the Ziegfeld Follies. Inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame in 1970

name: Ted Snyder
comments: Popular songwriter inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame in 1970

name: Fisk Jubilee Singers
comments: African American a capella singing ensemble formed in 1871, performing mostly gospel songs. It has disbanded from time-to-time, but a group associated with Fisk University that traces its routes back to the original ensemble exists to this date. Their first recordings were released on Victor in February 1910.

name: The Three Sounds
aliases: The Three Sounds featuring Gene Harris

name: Maxine Sullivan
aliases: Maxine Sullivan & Her Swedish Jazz All Stars
comments: Jazz and blues singer, who won fame in the 1930s with swing renditions of traditional songs. By the late 1930s Sullivan became one of the foremost women in jazz.  A black, female vocalist in America, she inspired a generation of young musicians like Ella Fitzgerald. Though largely absent from the jazz scene in the 1950s, she returned to perform in the late 1960s, at one point turning out an album every three months. She never retired and continued to work till her death.

name: Frank Boeijen [NL1]
comments: Singer and guitarist from Nijmegen best known for songs like "Kronenburg Park" (Ga die wereld uit)" about a prostitute, "Zwart Wit" about the racial murder of Kerwin Duinmeijer in Amsterdam and "Twee gezichten" about a split personality. Having been in the music business for 25 years he received the Edison award for his career achievements in 2005.

name: Friso Wiegersma
comments: Lyricist and painter, who was born in Deurne, where his father was a general practitioner. He was the partner of Wim Sonneveld, for whom he translated Jean Ferrat's "La montagne" using the alias Hugo Verhage. His Dutch lyrics paint a nostalgic picture of the village, Deurne, where Wiegersma was born and the cover became a classic song for Sonneveld.

name: Lenny Kuhr
comments: Singer and songwriter. Winner of the Eurovision Song Contest in 1969.

name: Stephan Sulke
comments: Born in Shanghai, China of Jews who had fled Berlin, Germany just ahead of the Nazis, Sulke grew up primarily in Switzerland, where he and his mother returned after World War II.  Sulke is a composer, guitarist and keyboardist.

name: Ramona Church
comments: Bluegrass banjo player and singer from North Carolina.

name: Don Rich [US1]
comments: Rich was born in the state of Washington but he is best known as a major architect of California's "Bakersfield Sound." He was lead guitarist, harmony singer and fiddle player with Buck Owens and the Buckaroos. He died in a motorcycle accident when he was still in his early 30s.

name: Wake the Dead
comments: California based "Celtic jam band". Quite some of their recordings are medleys of Grateful Dead songs and (mainly) Irish traditionals. Discovered by Bob Weir, who also invited them to open for Ratdog, and initiated their first album to be released on Grateful Dead Records

Cleveland later married there and started a family. Soon after, Cleveland migrated to Cleveland, Ohio. Copies of his most popular recording "Love Is a Trap" have been found on both Nosnibor Records and Alley Cat

name: Bartender

They have unmistakably developed their own sound and performed in Italy, Great Britain, Ireland, Germany, USA and China.

name: The Impressions

name: Gil Scott-Heron

By many considered one of the most revolutionary engineers/producers ever, he is probably best known for founding/heading the groundbreaking ON-U Sound label, producing/working with many Reggae/Dub key artists and his extraordinary remixes of tracks by Depeche Mode and many more.

name: The Sensations [US]

This is the group that first recorded for Atco in 1955.  Later Yvonne married Frank Baker and became known as Yvonne Baker. By 1958 the group broke up. However, a few years later Yvonne Baker and Alfonso Howell decided to reform the Sensations. In 1961 the other members were George Minor and Richard Curtain and this group recorded for Argo.

name: Bonnie Lou [US]
aliases: Bonnie Lou and The Dixie Partners
comments: Country music & bluegrass singer, guitarist and television performer from Asheville, North Carolina. She was best known for performing with her husband, Buster Moore, whom she married in 1945. He gave her the stage name, "Bonnie Lou," and they performed as "Bonnie Lou & Buster."

name: Bonnie Lou & Buster
comments: Country & bluegrass duo consisting of Herbert "Buster" Moore and his wife, Margaret "Bonnie Lou" Moore. They were married in 1945 and had radio shows in North Carolina, Tennessee and Virginia for several years. By 1953 they performed regularly on live television in Johnson City, Virginia. Their syndicated television show, which originated from Knoxville (WATE-TV), ran for 28 years beginning in 1954. In 1972 they began a long run at Dollywood presenting their Smoky Mountain Hayride show at the Pigeon Forge Coliseum. They retired in 1994.
